Upon starting eucalyptus will generate a new key ini file (this file can be specified with "session.keyini" in console.ini) if it doesn't already exist.

In the case of an environment where eucalyptus doesn't have write access to where the file should be created such as a RHEL init script you can use the following logic:

{code:none}
#!/bin/bash

KEYFILE=/tmp/session-keys.ini
KEYMGT=/home/rocky/dev/projects/eucalyptus/koala/git-eucalyptus/koala/koala/keymgt.py

if [ ! -f "$KEYFILE" ]; then
    python "$KEYMGT" "$KEYFILE"
fi
{code}

[~Rocky], permissions on the file should be set before any sensitive data is written into that (otherwise, it creates a race condition). Setting a restrictive umask before creating a file will ensure that the file is created with proper permissions. Something like that:
{code}
old_umask = os.umask(0o177) 
try:
    # create and write 
finally:
    os.umask(old_umask)
{code}
